Cheese example

Week 4

As cheese ages, various chemical processes take place that determine the taste of the final product.

This dataset (cheese) contains concentrations of various chemicals in 30 samples of mature cheddar cheese, and a subjective measure of taste for each sample.

  • The variables Acetic and H2S are the natural logarithm of the concentration of acetic acid and hydrogen sulphide respectively.
  • The variable Lactic has not been transformed.
  • The data are from Moore, David S., and George P. McCabe (1989). Introduction to the Practice of Statistics.

The purpose of the analysis is to understand the influence of the different variables on the overall taste score.

  • What follows is the generation of the standard diagnostic plots for the multiple regression of taste on Acetic, Lactic and H2S.
  • In this case, the conclusion is that the regression assumptions appear to be reasonable and there are no influential points of concern.

pacman::p_load(tidyverse, gglm)

4 Full model

cheese_lm <- lm(taste ~ ., data = cheese)
summary(cheese_lm)

5 Residuals

cheese_res <- 
  broom::augment(cheese_lm) %>% 
  add_column(studres = MASS::studres(cheese_lm))
cheese_res
cheese_res %>% 
  ggplot(aes(.resid, .std.resid)) + 
  geom_point()

cheese_res %>% 
  ggplot(aes(.resid, studres)) + 
  geom_point()

5.1 Standardised residuals

cheese_res %>% 
  ggplot(aes(.fitted, .std.resid)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(span = 1)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

cheese_res %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Acetic, .std.resid)) + 
  geom_point()

cheese_res %>% 
  ggplot(aes(H2S, .std.resid)) + 
  geom_point()

cheese_res %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Lactic, .std.resid)) + 
  geom_point()

cheese_res %>%
